text.text: In spite of the cries from unwanted cats and dogs, Battersea is in fact a cheery place where secret gardens, Scalextric and buttplug cocktails are in abundance. Sound daunting? Don't fret, we'll hold your hand. Let's have it large.

tip.text:
This popular coffee shop comes to Battersea from Melbourne via Cuba. Named after a line from founder Cameron’s favourite song, expect a hispanic influence in Birdhouse’s food and a recurring avian theme in the artwork. The minimalist grey and yellow colour scheme makes for a modern interior, while quirks such as the joiners bench worktop and X-ray screen menu add character to this cosy hangout.

Everything here is made in-house, from the excellent coffee to the naughty cakes. The Birdhouse bread & butter pudding is made with croissant and chocolate chips! Other reasons for paying a visit include the brunches - pulled pork baked beans on toast with cheddar and a slow-cooked egg - and the bocaditos (Cuban sandwiches).

tip.text:
It might not look like much from the outside (or inside), but believe us when we say that Mien Tay is well worth investigating. The interior is basic but you won't forget the tables anytime soon - imported from Vietnam, they're hollowed out and feature mini, matchstick model villages observable through the glass.

South Vietnamese food really is something special: delightful flavours and just the right amount of spice. We couldn't get enough of the monkfish - in crispy salt and pepper form to start, before coming in the guise of an absolutely stunning curry. Wash it down with a Saigon beer and we promise that you'll be going home with a huge grin on your face.

text.text: We’d forgive you for walking past Mien Tay without venturing inside, but believe us when we say that Southern Vietnam is being represented in South London in a big way. Locals can’t get enough of it, it’s always packed and you might even have to settle for sharing a table - but boy are the flavours serious. Who cares about decor and privacy when you’ve got food this good? We sure don’t.
Best for... getting your inner-child pissed

tip.text:
This place is so much more than a pub. All ales served at The Four Thieves are brewed in-house, literally - the brewery is slap bang on the ground floor, just sat right there. The Boat House next door is a separate comedy venue complete with a ship bar. An actual ship. Oh, and there’s also a gin garden (the back bar is stocked with 70+ gins).

That’s all downstairs. Upstairs, the enormous arcade is the stuff of dreams. We’re talking ping-pong tables and retro pinball machines. The best bit comes courtesy of the Racing Bug residency: scaled up Scalextric = Formula fun. Weekly antics include comedy nights, bottomless brunch on the weekend and resident eccentric Boogaloo Stu’s Dirty Bingo (not for the faint-hearted).

text.text: Plunge into the world of Four Thieves on a Friday and you might not resurface in time for work on Monday. We’re still trying to get our heads around this place... comedy, quizzes, bingo, dance offs and a bottomless brunch to boot! Ever played Bomberman on a projector? Nah, didn’t think so. Warn your liver, assemble your mates and dive headfirst into this barmy bar.
Best for... scenic strolls and wildlife watching

tip.text: We like to think of Battersea as a low-key kind of park, not one to blow its own trumpet, instead going about its business quietly and confidently. It's the perfect spot for a walk or picnic - there are six gardens to choose from and a healthy ecosystem means wildlife all year round. Throw in some beautiful views of the Thames, a gallery in a Grade II listed building, a golden buddha, and pedalos on the lake for good measure and you're onto a fine park.

text.text: Sometimes, it’s nice to have it large out in the open air - fresh grass, ponds, ducks and all that good stuff. Take a break from Battersea’s high streets and have yourself a stroll or pedal even (bike or pedalo) while digesting those views of the Thames. If you start displaying cultural withdrawal symptoms then you can always swing by the Pump House Gallery to check out some art.
Best for... dinner by the river

tip.text:
Not the easiest place to get to, but once you turn into this welcoming courtyard by the warf you feel like you're in on a little Battersea secret. Its pretty darn scenic, with hanging plants, fairy lights and moored house boats. Nutbourne has a fancy country pub feel — pale wood and wicker chairs, dog regulars, comedy pigs in parachutes hanging from the ceiling.

The pub vibes end there though. Everything on the menu is pretty carefully thought out — down to the delicate mushroom profiterole we were offered as an amuse bouche. Some of the more elaborate dishes could be accused of over-egging it but the duck salad— sheesh, we could eat it again and again.

text.text: Tucked away in a welcoming courtyard with moored house boats, hanging plants and fairy lights, Nutbourne combines the vibe of a fancy country pub with the well-constructed menu of a fine dining restaurant. After something romantic and slightly elaborate, head here and make sure you order the duck salad.
Best for... the three Ds: dinner, drinks & decor

tip.text:
POWDERKEG’s extensive cocktail list raises one of modern man’s greatest predicaments - which cocktail to indulge in first?

We reckon start with ‘The Powder Monkey’ made with apple infused whiskey, Saliza Amaretto, apple and lemon juice, white sugar and egg white. SO. GOOD. But if you're the type of person to pick a race horse for it's name then 'The last words of Professor Ampleforth' is for you - Bathtub Gin, lime cordial, green chartreuse and bergamot bitters are fused together in its own glass of billowing smoke.

The cocktails are only half the deal. The food is incredible. Advice: If you're going to have only one starter make it the homemade scotch egg.

text.text: This lot have a motto: honouring tradition, subverting convention. The classic meets the slightly kooky in this old colonial haunt; they have a ‘resident illusionist’ and the restaurant is in a glasshouse, so you can dine romantically under vines and whatnot. Their cocktail game is strong too, so load up on delicious grub under some foliage before hitting up the bar. But prepare for a hit on the disposable.
Best for... getting brunched in the face

tip.text:
With furniture crafted from a single Elm tree, floor to ceiling windows and a bespoke hexagonal clad bar, Story Coffee is channeling that minimalist, Scandinavian vibe.

This is a sweet spot to clear your head with a good cup of joe - the beans are sourced from Square Mile Coffee Roasters and The Barn in Berlin. Food-wise they serve a selection of pastries and are famed for their healthy, hearty brunch options - in our opinion you can’t beat the smashed avo with smoked salmon on sourdough toast. This is definitely the MVP of the Battersea coffee scene.

text.text: Story Coffee is all about soothing Scandinavian interiors, fantastic coffee and brunches that promise to be kind to your figure. tip.text:
Unless you take your time machine over to Paris, you're not finding a place like Le QuecumBar anywhere else. This is an intimate, mad little den dedicated to live Gypsy Swing, and the legendary guitarist Django Reinhardt. The music is amazing, the wine is flowing, and there's a classic French brasserie menu to get through as well. If you're after something a little different, hightail it down here.

Sundays and Mondays are ticketed concert nights showcasing some of the best Gypsy Swing players around. Grab tickets on their site.

text.text: Yes, like the veg. What’s the one thing cooler than a cucumber? 1930s Paris. Drop into this delightful little spot for the full experience: live Gypsy swing, Coq au Vin and a darling garden all atwinkle with fairy lights. A welcome change from the typical high street joints, Le QuecumBar is refreshing and full of personality. We like personality.
